Slide 1 — Title: Medical Interpreting Using AI
“Today, we’re going to explore how artificial intelligence is being used in medical interpreting. AI is becoming more common in healthcare communication, but it brings both opportunities and risks. My goal is to give you a balanced understanding of what AI can do, where it falls short, and who is responsible when things go wrong.”

Slide 2 — What AI Can Do in Medical Interpreting
“AI can be extremely helpful in certain parts of the interpreting workflow. For example, it can provide quick translations for simple, low‑risk conversations like appointment reminders or basic intake questions. It can also support interpreters by helping with terminology lookup or generating draft translations. And in areas where interpreters are not readily available, AI can help bridge basic communication gaps. The key point is that AI can enhance access and efficiency when used appropriately.”

Slide 3 — Limitations and Risks
“However, AI has significant limitations in medical settings. It struggles with accents, dialects, idioms, and cultural nuance. It can’t ask clarifying questions, which is essential in healthcare communication. AI may mistranslate medical terminology, and there’s always a risk of privacy issues. Because of these limitations, AI should not be used alone for emergencies, mental health encounters, informed consent, or any complex clinical discussion. These situations require human judgment, empathy, and precision.”

Slide 4 — Responsibility When AI Goes Wrong
“One of the most important questions is: who is responsible if AI makes a mistake? Legally and ethically, responsibility still falls on humans and institutions. Healthcare providers are responsible for ensuring accurate communication. Hospitals must choose safe tools and follow language‑access laws. AI vendors are responsible for transparency, but they often limit their liability. And if interpreters are involved, they must use professional judgment and verify AI output. The key takeaway is that AI cannot be held responsible — humans remain accountable.”

Slide 5 — Best Practices & Conclusion
“To use AI safely, we need clear guidelines. AI should be limited to low‑risk communication, and trained interpreters should always be offered for medical encounters. Staff need training on AI’s limitations, and any use of AI should be documented. Ultimately, the safest model is human‑led interpreting supported by AI tools. AI can enhance our work, but it cannot replace the expertise, cultural understanding, and ethical responsibility of trained interpreters.”
